**Step 1 – Determine the reaction entropy at 298 K**

\[
\Delta G^{\circ}_{298}= \Delta H^{\circ}_{298}-T_{298}\,\Delta S^{\circ}
\]

\[
\Delta S^{\circ}= \frac{\Delta H^{\circ}_{298}-\Delta G^{\circ}_{298}}{T_{298}}
               =\frac{-5797\;{\rm kJ\,mol^{-1}}-(-6333\;{\rm kJ\,mol^{-1}})}{298\;{\rm K}}
               =\frac{536\;{\rm kJ\,mol^{-1}}}{298\;{\rm K}}
               =1.80\;{\rm kJ\,mol^{-1}\,K^{-1}}
\]

\[
\Delta S^{\circ}=1.80\times10^{3}\;{\rm J\,mol^{-1}\,K^{-1}}
\]

**Step 2 – Estimate the Gibbs energy at 37 °C (310 K)**  

Assume that \(\Delta H^{\circ}\) and \(\Delta S^{\circ}\) are essentially temperature‑independent over the small interval 298 K → 310 K.

\[
\Delta G^{\circ}_{310}= \Delta H^{\circ}_{298}-T_{310}\,\Delta S^{\circ}
\]

\[
\Delta G^{\circ}_{310}= -5797\;{\rm kJ\,mol^{-1}}-(310\;{\rm K})(1.80\;{\rm kJ\,mol^{-1}\,K^{-1}})
\]

\[
\Delta G^{\circ}_{310}= -5797\;{\rm kJ\,mol^{-1}}-557.6\;{\rm kJ\,mol^{-1}}
                     = -6354.6\;{\rm kJ\,mol^{-1}}
\]

**Step 3 – Additional non‑expansion work obtainable**

The maximum non‑PV (e.g., electrical) work that can be extracted is the Gibbs free‑energy change.  
The extra work obtained by raising the temperature from 298 K to 310 K is therefore

\[
\Delta W_{\text{extra}} = \Delta G^{\circ}_{310}-\Delta G^{\circ}_{298}
                         = -6354.6\;{\rm kJ\,mol^{-1}}-(-6333\;{\rm kJ\,mol^{-1}})
                         = -21.6\;{\rm kJ\,mol^{-1}}
\]

The negative sign indicates that more work can be obtained; the magnitude of the additional non‑expansion work is about **22 kJ mol⁻¹**.

\[
\boxed{\,\approx -22\ \text{kJ mol}^{-1}\,}
\]

