The electricfield of an infinite uniformly‑charged plane is constant:

\[
E=\frac{|\sigma|}{2\varepsilon_0}
\]

with \(\sigma =-2.0\times10^{-6}\,\text{C/m}^2\) (use the magnitude).  

\[
\varepsilon_0 = 8.854\times10^{-12}\ \text{C}^2\!/\!\text{N·m}^2
\]

\[
E = \frac{2.0\times10^{-6}}{2(8.854\times10^{-12})}
   = \frac{2.0\times10^{-6}}{1.7708\times10^{-11}}
   \approx 1.13\times10^{5}\ \text{N/C}
\]

The electron (charge magnitude \(e = 1.602\times10^{-19}\,\text{C}\)) feels a force \(F = eE\) opposite its motion, so the work done by the field over a distance \(d\) is \(-eEd\).  
Setting the loss of kinetic energy equal to this work:

\[
-\;eEd = -K_i \quad\Longrightarrow\quad d = \frac{K_i}{eE}
\]

\[
K_i = 1.60\times10^{-17}\ \text{J}
\]

