m=\frac{M}{N_{\!A}}=
   \frac{44.01\times10^{-3}}{6.022\times10^{23}}
   \approx 7.31\times10^{-26}\ {\rm kg}
\]

For collisions of two identical molecules the reduced mass is  

\[
\mu =\frac{m}{2}=3.66\times10^{-26}\ {\rm kg}
\]

---

**Step 3 – Average relative speed**

For identical particles the average relative speed is  

\[
\bar v_{\rm rel}= \sqrt{\frac{16k_{\mathrm B}T}{\pi m}}
\]

\[
\bar v_{\rm rel}= \sqrt{\frac{16(1.380649\times10^{-23})(298)}
                              {\pi(7.31\times10^{-26})}}
                \approx 5.35\times10^{2}\ {\rm m\,s^{-1}}
\]

---

**Step 4 – Collision cross‑section**

A typical kinetic diameter for CO₂ is \(d\approx3.3\ \text{Å}=3.3\times10^{-10}\ {\rm m}\).

\[
\sigma =\pi d^{2}= \pi(3.3\times10^{-10})^{2}
        \approx 3.42\times10^{-19}\ {\rm m^{2}}
\]

---

**Step 5 – Total collision frequency per unit volume**

The number of collisions per unit volume per unit time is  

\[
Z = \frac12\,n^{2}\,\sigma\,\bar v_{\rm rel}
\]

\[
\begin{aligned}
Z &=\frac12\,(2.46\times10^{25})^{2}
        (3.42\times10^{-19})
        (5.35\times10^{2})\\[2mm]
  &\approx \frac12\,(6.06\times10^{50})
        (3.42\times10^{-19})
        (5.35\times10^{2})\\[2mm]
  &\approx 5.6\times10^{34}\ {\rm m^{-3}\,s^{-1}}
\end{aligned}
\]

---

\[
\boxed{Z \;\approx\;5.6\times10^{34}\ {\rm m^{-3}\,s^{-1}}}
\]

#### 5.6

For a reversible (Carnot) refrigerator the coefficient ofperformance is  

\[
\text{COP}= \frac{Q_{\text{cold}}}{W}= \frac{T_c}{T_h-T_c},
\]

where the temperatures must be in an absolute scale.  
Using the Rankine scale (\(R = ^\circ\!F + 459.67\)):

\[
\begin{aligned}
T_h &= 65^\circ\!F = 65+459.67 = 524.67\;R,\\[2mm]
T_{\text{fridge}} &= 36^\circ\!F = 36+459.67 = 495.67\;R,\\[2mm]
T_{\text{freezer}} &= 0^\circ\!F = 0+459.67 = 459.67\;R.
\end{aligned}
\]

---

### COP of the refrigerator

\[
\text{COP}_{\text{fridge}} = \frac{T_{\text{fridge}}}{T_h-T_{\text{fridge}}}
= \frac{495.67}{524.67-495.67}
= \frac{495.67}{29.00}
\approx 17.09 .
\]

### COP of the freezer

\[
\text{COP}_{\text{freezer}} = \frac{T_{\text{freezer}}}{T_h-T_{\text{freezer}}}
= \frac{459.67}{524.67-459.67}
= \frac{459.67}{65.00}
\approx 7.07 .
\]

---

The work required per unit of heat extracted is the reciprocal of the COP.  
Hence the factor by which it is more expensive to extract the same amount of heat from the freezer than from the refrigerator is

\[
\frac{W_{\text{freezer}}/Q}{W_{\text{fridge}}/Q}
= \frac{1/\text{COP}_{\text{freezer}}}{1/\text{COP}_{\text{fridge}}}
= \frac{\text{COP}_{\text{fridge}}}{\text{COP}_{\text{freezer}}}
= \frac{17.09}{7.07}
\approx 2.42 .
\]

\[
\boxed{\,\approx 2.4\,}
\]

Thus, extracting the same amount of heat from the freezer requires about **2.4 times more work** (i.e., is 2.4‑times more expensive) than extracting it from the refrigerator.

The horse’s work can be found from the heat supplied to the water.

**1. Energy needed to heat thewater**

\[
\begin{aligned}
m_{\text{water}} &= 11.6\ \text{kg}=1.16\times10^{4}\ \text{g}\\[2pt]
c_{\text{water}} &= 4.18\ \frac{\text{J}}{\text{g·K}}\\[2pt]
\Delta T &= 355\ \text{K}-273\ \text{K}=82\ \text{K}\\[2pt]
Q &= m\,c\,\Delta T = (1.16\times10^{4}\,\text{g})(4.18\,\frac{\text{J}}{\text{g·K}})(82\ \text{K})\\
  &= 3.98\times10^{6}\ \text{J}
\end{aligned}
\]

**2. Power delivered by the horse**

Time for heating: \(2.5\ \text{h}=2.5\times3600\ \text{s}=9.0\times10^{3}\ \text{s}\).

\[
P = \frac{Q}{t}= \frac{3.98\times10^{6}\ \text{J}}{9.0\times10^{3}\ \text{s}}
   \approx 4.42\times10^{2}\ \text{W}
\]

**3. Work the horse could do in 2.5 min**

\[
t_{\text{lift}} = 2.5\ \text{min}=150\ \text{s}
\]
\[
W = P\,t_{\text{lift}} = (4.42\times10^{2}\ \text{W})(150\ \text{s})
   \approx 6.63\times10^{4}\ \text{J}
\]

**4. Height the 225 kg weight could be raised**

\[
W = m g h \quad\Longrightarrow\quad
h = \frac{W}{m g}
   = \frac{6.63\times10^{4}\ \text{J}}{(225\ \text{kg})(9.81\ \text{m/s}^2)}
   \approx 3.0\times10^{1}\ \text{m}
\]

\[
\boxed{h \approx 30\ \text{m}}
\]

#### 30

The quantum yield (Φ) is the ratio of the number of molecules that react to the number of photons absorbed.

**1. Molecules that reacted**

\[
n_{\text{reacted}} = 2.5\ \text{mmol}=2.5\times10^{-3}\ \text{mol}
\]

\[
N_{\text{reacted}} = n_{\text{reacted}}\;N_A
               = 2.5\times10^{-3}\ \text{mol}\times 6.022\times10^{23}\ \text{mol}^{-1}
               = 1.51\times10^{21}\ \text{molecules}
\]

**2. Photons absorbed**

Energy supplied by the lamp:

\[
E_{\text{total}} = P\,t = (100\ \text{W})(27.0\ \text{s}) = 2.70\times10^{3}\ \text{J}
\]

Energy of one photon at 280 nm:

\[
E_{\text{photon}} = \frac{hc}{\lambda}
= \frac{(6.626\times10^{-34}\ \text{J·s})(3.00\times10^{8}\ \text{m·s}^{-1})}{280\times10^{-9}\ \text{m}}
= 7.10\times10^{-19}\ \text{J}
\]

Number of photons absorbed:

\[
N_{\text{photons}} = \frac{E_{\text{total}}}{E_{\text{photon}}}
= \frac{2.70\times10^{3}\ \text{J}}{7.10\times10^{-19}\ \text{J/photon}}
= 3.80\times10^{21}\ \text{photons}
\]

**3. Quantum yield**

\[
\Phi = \frac{N_{\text{reacted}}}{N_{\text{photons}}}
      = \frac{1.51\times10^{21}}{3.80\times10^{21}}
      \approx 0.40
\]

\[
\boxed{ \Phi \approx 0.40 }
\]

The equilibrium condition is obtained from the pressure‑dependence of the Gibbs energy for the two phases (treated as incompressible):

\[
\Delta G(P)=\Delta G^{\circ}+ \Delta V\,(P-P^{\circ})=0
\]

\[
\Rightarrow\; P_{\text{eq}} = P^{\circ}-\frac{\Delta G^{\circ}}{\Delta V}
\]

---

### 1.  Standard Gibbs‑energy difference  

\[
\Delta G^{\circ}=G^{\circ}_{\text{diamond}}-G^{\circ}_{\text{graphite}}
               = 2.90\;\text{kJ mol}^{-1}=2.90\times10^{3}\;\text{J mol}^{-1}
\]

---

### 2.  Molar volumes from the densities  

Molar mass of carbon: \(M = 12.011\;\text{g mol}^{-1}=0.012011\;\text{kg mol}^{-1}\).

\[
V_{\text{graphite}} = \frac{M}{\rho_{\text{graphite}}}
                     =\frac{0.012011\;\text{kg mol}^{-1}}{2.25\;\text{kg L}^{-1}}
                     =5.34\times10^{-3}\;\text{L mol}^{-1}=5.34\;\text{cm}^{3}\,\text{mol}^{-1}
\]

\[
V_{\text{diamond}} = \frac{M}{\rho_{\text{diamond}}}
                    =\frac{0.012011}{3.52}
                    =3.41\times10^{-3}\;\text{L mol}^{-1}=3.41\;\text{cm}^{3}\,\text{mol}^{-1}
\]

\[
\Delta V = V_{\text{diamond}}-V_{\text{graphite}}
         = 3.41-5.34 = -1.93\;\text{cm}^{3}\,\text{mol}^{-1}
         = -1.93\times10^{-6}\;\text{m}^{3}\,\text{mol}^{-1}
\]

---

### 3.  Equilibrium pressure  

\[
P_{\text{eq}} = P^{\circ}-\frac{\Delta G^{\circ}}{\Delta V}
               = (1\;\text{bar})-\frac{2.90\times10^{3}\;\text{J mol}^{-1}}
                                   {-1.93\times10^{-6}\;\text{m}^{3}\,\text{mol}^{-1}}
\]

\[
\frac{\Delta G^{\circ}}{\Delta V}= -1.50\times10^{9}\;\text{Pa}
\]

\[
P_{\text{eq}} = 1\times10^{5}\;\text{Pa}+1.50\times10^{9}\;\text{Pa}
               = 1.51\times10^{9}\;\text{Pa}
\]

Convert to bar (\(1\;\text{bar}=10^{5}\;\text{Pa}\)):

\[
P_{\text{eq}} = \frac{1.51\times10^{9}}{10^{5}} \approx 1.5\times10^{4}\;\text{bar}
\]

---

\[
\boxed{ \; \approx 1.5 \times 10^{4}\ \text{bar} \;}
\]

So graphite and diamond are in equilibrium at about **\(1.5 \times 10^{4}\) bar** (≈ 15 kbar) at 298 K.
